        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Mobile</placeName> <date>29<hi rend="sup">th</hi> Decr. 1850</date></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Yours of <date>18<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> reached me this morning<lb/> &#38; I am obliged to you for your free &#38; friendly com&#61;<lb/>ments on my brochures&#44; which I did not send you<lb/> with any desire of <del>my</del> being noticed in the occident.<lb/> You had been so kind as reply to the queries which<lb/> I had propounded&#44; &#38; as a matter of courtesy I sent<lb/> these essays to you&#44; not hoping that you would coin<lb/>cide with me in opinion&#44; but hoping they might show<lb/> you what the enemy were doing &#38; afford you some<lb/> material for reflection.</p>
			<p>A letter is not the place to reopen this discussion. You<lb/> believe in the strict authenticity of the Pentateuch&#44; which<lb/> I with <persName>Gesenius</persName>&#44; <persName>De Wette</persName>&#44; <persName>Eichhorn</persName>&#44; <persName>Munk</persName>&#44; <persName>Cohen</persName>&#44; &#38;<lb/> many other first rate Hebrew scholars&#44; do not&#44; to say the<lb/> least the question is unsettled&#44; while the Egyptian dis&#61;<lb/>coveries go far I think to strengthen the party opposed<lb/> to you. Admitting the antiquity of the Pentateuch&#44;<lb/> this is no proof of its historical accuracy&#8212;modern sci&#61;<lb/>ence I think has clearly upset the plain &#38; simple account<lb/> of the Creation in Genesis&#44; &#38; I think the Genealogies&#44; &#38; Chro&#61;<lb/>nology of the Hebrew text <del>is</del> are pretty generally abandoned by<lb/> scholars&#8212;<hi rend="underline">certainly</hi> the chronologies of <placeName>Egypt</placeName> &#38; <placeName>China</placeName><lb/> destroy that of Genesis I think&#44; &#38; this book <del>itself</del> has state<lb/>ments written itself irreconcilable with each other all<lb/> this of course you deny.</p>
			<p>My object was not <hi rend="underline">theological</hi> discussion. I entered<lb/> this field because the Unity of Races could not be dis&#61;<lb/>cussed apart from the Bible&#44; &#38; I wished to cut loose what</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>I considered great <hi rend="underline">practical truths</hi> from the trammels<lb/> which find it. If there <hi rend="underline">is</hi> a <hi rend="underline">gradation</hi> in Races&#44; the<lb/> fact is too important to be smothered&#44; by human<lb/> opinions.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In reply to your comments on my note on<lb/> page 40 of &#8220;Chronology&#8221; I need only say that if you will<lb/> recur to it you will see that you have been led into<lb/> an error by reading <persName>Moses</persName> instead of <persName><hi rend="underline">Menes</hi></persName> the first<lb/> of the Pharaohs&#8212;I regard two facts as <add>&#63;</add> which are<lb/> incompatible with <hi rend="underline">Genesis</hi> as we have it viz the Chronology&#8212;<lb/>&#38; the proof of distinct Races as far back as the 3d or 4th<lb/> Dynasties. Though <hi rend="underline">exactness</hi> cannot be attained as<lb/> to the date of <persName><hi rend="underline">Menes</hi></persName>&#44; I think <hi rend="underline">all</hi> Egyptologists place<lb/> him <del>far beyond</del> &#38; African <hi rend="underline">Races</hi> far beyond your<lb/> date of the flood</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I regret very much that on page 17 of Phy<add>&#63;</add> List of<lb/> Jews I have put words in your mouth which you<lb/> did not use. The latter part of the paragraph to<lb/> which you allude is from <persName><hi rend="underline">Buchanan</hi></persName> &#38; the printer or<lb/> editor in <placeName>Charleston</placeName> must have made the mistake. I<lb/> never saw the <hi rend="underline">proofs</hi>&#44; &#38; this is but one of many blunders<lb/> they have made for me on different occasions.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Smyths</persName> critique on my book is too weak &#38; ungentlemanly<lb/> to deserve a reply. <persName>Howes</persName> is not much better &#38; I replied<lb/> merely to keep the subject alive. <persName>Bachmans</persName> book is a rare combi<lb/>nation of biggotry&#44; talent&#44; &#38; learning. <persName>Agassiz</persName> &#38; <persName>Morton</persName> have killed<lb/> him so dead that he can never kick again</p>
          <p rend="indent(8)">very respectfully</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)">your obt. servt</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">J. C. Mott</persName></p>
			<p>To <addressee>Isaac Leeser Esq</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Phia.</placeName></p>
          
        </body>
